betterquesting:10.desc:8:
§rWhen a tool loses all of its durabilty it is unusable until you repair it in the Tool Station with the same material as the tool head, or craft it together with a matching sharping kit.

If you place your Pattern Chest next to your Stencil Table and Part Builder, it will add its functinalty to both.

Place Blank Patterns into the Stencil Table to make patterns. Place patterns into the Part Builder along with a material (like wood) to make tool parts. Combine tool parts in the Tool Station. 

Quest will complete with any combination of parts. (Or a finished pickaxe)
Build a Mattock or Shovel and Axe. This can be completed with any combanation of parts.

§bThis can be completed with any combination of parts, and with any of the three base tinkers swords.§r

Flint, bones, and cactus make good early game weapon parts. Look in the book to see the options avalible.

§6These are some of the items that can be used as modifers for your weapons!
Trying to find stuff is like catching a phantom sometimes.
Standard gathering routine.
Used for more advanced machinery.

Early game Embers!
Hold the Tinker's Lens in your hand or off hand to see what various blocks are used for.

Walk around with the Atmospheric gauge to find an Ember rich location to place your Bore.

No gui means it can be hard to know whats going on inside the machines, so craft up some dials to attach to them!


Refer to the Codex for more in depth information on any of these quests, as well as more information on Embers in general.
Here's a few logistical solutions for your needs.

Place this within 3 spaces of bedrock, and pipe coal or another burnable material through the top hole, and it will start mining Ember! This expands into a 3x3 structure.

Place another §6Mechanical Core§r on the top center of the Bore for more access.

How to use:

Place any block, then place the projector on top, facing the direction you want the field to be. Right click the projector to see the placement guide for the projector across from it. Right click either projector to see where to place the two side projectors. Be sure that each projector is facing in, and that the ground is flat.

If assembeled correctly, an §e§6orange holographic cube§r will form in the center. This is where you will construct the recipes.

For every arrow beyond the first, you will need each projector to be one block higher.

Using Soul Vials, create new items.

You can use a §dPowered Spawner§r on Capture mode to automatically fill Soul Vials!
This one will be tricky to automate. You need a way to place the Empowered blocks, as well as a way to break and collect the Unempowered blocks.
Magic is fun!

Upgrading your equipment with metal!

Place the Melter on top of the lava filled tank. Insert 2 gold or clay, then right click the attached faucet to pour it onto a casting table with a tool part, ingot, plate, or gear, to make a cast.

§cThe Melter can only hold one type of liquid at a time!§r

§bThe Token can be spent in the Shop chapter.

§5The §5Tier 6 Seed can be converted down at a 1:2 ratio, then back up. Choose wisely!
First step to making the Smeltery. You will need much more than this to make it, but this should be enough for your starting needs.
Once you have your cast made, insert the metal of choice to be melted. We are going to need iron for this quest.

Powered by a laser of gigantic proportions, this multiblock can forge together some of the rarest and most expensive materials.

Replace the Crystaltine Block with a block of §bCrystal Matrix§r to halve the fluid input.

Assemble the shown structure inside the orange 3x3x3 cube between the Projectors, then throw the catalyst in the field.

You can also use this block on the Ember Bore and similar to increase the accessible slots.
Requires 2000 heat.
Needed for making some plates and dense plates.

Extractor conected to an inventory, pipe connected to where you want it to end up at. 

§cYou need a redstone signal to extract.

Looking at the top and bottom of this with the Tinker's Lens will show us that solid embers need to be piped into the bottom, then Ember power comes out the top. Attach an Ember Emitter to the top to be able to transfer it, then a Receptor attached to the Copper Cell, or Ember powered machine.

§6Shift-right click §rwith the Tinker's Hammer on the Receptor, then §6right click §rthe Emitter. After supplying a §credstone signal §rto the Emitter, you should start to see Embers being transferred! Embers can travel a maximum of 25 blocks.

§bEmbers can also be used as a basic source of RF for some of your early game machines. Simply attach a Receptor onto whatever needs power!

Attach an Ember Receptor to the correct side of the Melter. To connect the two ember transmitters shift-right click the Receptor then right click the Emitter. §cUse the lever to activate the Emitter.§r

You can right click on the melter to place things into it, drop them in, or pipe them. 

This is one of the first methods of ore doubling.
Right click the pump with these. Can't make Aluminum until you get the Arc Furnace.

These work the same as the item pipes. 

§c§cMake sure you have a lever to activate the Extractor.

§rFluid Pipes have a flow direction, which you can see when you hold the §bTinkers Lens§r. Piping multiple fluids through a single set of pipes might lead to a headache!

Fluid goes in the Bottom, one empty block, then the Stamper above that. Right click with the stamp to attach, them power with Ember.

§6Be sure that your Ember Shards are placed before you start piping metal in!§r

Items are collected in a Bin below the Stamp Base, or dropped if there is no Bin.

§bThis is also a great way to make all the gears you'll be needing!
Cast out one of the five basic alloys to complete this chapter!

Welcome to §5Multiblock Madness§r! 

Most vanilla recipes are unchanged, so you can start at your own pace. Take you time setting up a base, or rush ahead with progression.

Recipes get progressively more expensive as you go through the pack, so stock up!

§cNote: This is not a skyblock! If you chose to take the Simple Void World portal block, you'll still have to make plenty of trips back to the Overworld. It also has a recipe later on in chapter 3.

This is basically a hand held book shelf. Craft it together with any book to add it.

Right click with it to open the book menu, then once you are done looking at whichever book just left click the air with it.

§bThe filled Tome is craftable, so if you do lose your Tome, just craft another. (It's the recipe with gold ingots)

You will need to go to the Betweenlands before you can craft your first backpack, the Lurker Skin Pouch.

In the meantime, have a Shulker box!

Right click with the Chisel to open the block chisel menu, then put something that can be chiseled, for example cobblestone. Then you click a variant to chisel all the cobble in the upper left slot into the one you picked. You can also leave a chiseled block in the slot, which will enable you to chisel inworld blocks of the same type with left click.

§d§rWe have a few very useful hotkeys to set up in this pack:

§2Better Questing: Opens the questbook.

§bOre Excavator: Holding down while using a tool will cause connected blocks to be harversted as well.

§6Find Me: Pushing while hovering oven an item will cause nearby chests containing that item to light up.



§rIf you are having trouble with a quest, read the discription!

When you see a red X§r, you will need to check it to complete the quest.
This pump needs a small amount of power in the top to run, as well as a redstone signal. Right click a side with the Hammer to change in/output.

Shift right click on each corner of a 3D craft, then place the Markers inside the Replicator. Link the last Marker to where you want the Builder to assemble the structure.

After receiving RF and the items, it will start to build.
Place one of these as a pipe, then right click it with the only thing you want to pass through it.
Upgrade a Gas Pump by right clicking with a Compressing Unit.

Can be placed in the body Bauble slot, and opened with a hotkey.

§bYou may notice a lot of single use crafted quests, such as this one, giving a choice for another of the same item. This is intended for players on a team.

Place the §5Flux Condenser§r on top of one of the jars, with the other four connected by tube to it. Then place the Lattices on top, all connected to the Condenser as well. 

Each of the outside jars will need to be filled with Essentia to activate the §5Condenser§r. Be sure to keep the Lattices clean by using a Filter on them when they get clogged.

Hold paper in your hand, and Charcoal in your off hand, then shift right click your Waystone to copy the strange symbols. This also requires a small amount of XP to create.





(or you can use the /home command, but thats not as cool)

Stores MORE fluid!

Place the Valve on top of the Reservoir. Fluid can be transferred through any of the sides or the bottom.

Place any tool or weapon in the center of the tool station along with a part to replace that part.

§bAdd these to your pickaxe for more specific Fossil drops.
When you melt an ore, some impurities are lost. If you attach this to the base of the melter when you melt down some ores, you can collect a second molten metal type.

Assemble a 4x4 base, then place 2 exterior layers, so you have a 2x2 open interior.

You have two options for heating: Advanced Solar Panels on each 4 corners (these need to be inset one block.)

Or you can use Heaters placed adjacent to a valve. §c§rRemember to set the RF usage in the machine!

Simply by supplying this with a steady source of water, you can increase your ember burning efficiency by 1.5. If you place it on a block of metal, then heat it up by surrounding it with lava or fire, you can get up to 6x efficiency!

§bTry placing this on a block of Dawnstone!

Place the Mechanical Actuator next to your Pump, which will then start picking up the water in the single block below it. 

You can also use Mechanical Actuator connected to a Mechanical Core on top of the Bore, for much better result.

§bDont forget to add a gear!

This handy device allows you to store xp.

§bThe Rod is required to store XP on a server.
Finding things is a challenge sometimes.

Picked as a flower in the overworld, or mined deep underground.

Magic Crystals have many uses in Wizardry
Who likes constantly going back underground?
Anyone standing next to the flower will find their xp being turned in mana.

The §dSteam Engine§r can either have coal and water piped into it, or steam.

A §dSteam Engine§r running on water and coal will produce §a20 rotational power§r, while one running on steam will produce §a40 RP§r.

Placing a §9Mini Boiler§r next to any Ember processing machine and filling it with water will create steam! Explosions are disabled in this pack, so no need to worry.

§6The Ember Bore can be made much faster by switching to mechanical power.§r

Axles go between the Steam engine output and the Gearbox, which has the input facing you when you place it. 

The Gearbox needs a gear on any face with an Axle to complete the connection.

Whenever you make a right turn with an Axle, you will need a Gearbox there.

§6Holding the Tinker's Lens in your offhand will be very helpful when setting up a Mechanical System!

§4Gearboxes and Mergeboxes may only be rotated with the Quartz Wrench!

Make a 3x3x3 cube, then hammer the front with your hammer.

Coal goes in, Coke Coal and Creosote Oil comes out.

Can also be used to create Charcoal.
This can be used to hide Conduits.
Place Scrap/boxes inside for UU Matter.
This material is used a lot in Mekanism machines!
Look up the recipe for molten Dawnstone to create.

Assemble a hollow 3x3x3 cube, then place the controller in the center of one of the layers. The drain can go anywere, but put it on the second row up, then attach the faucet to it. Place the table below the faucet.

§6You can increase the capacity by adding extra middle layers.

§rThe High Oven works by burning Coke Coal or §bAlumentum §rto produce heat. Once the heat is high enough, it will start the melting process. If it is hot enough, and you have the correct inputs, it can also create a few alloys.

After fueling with Coke Coal or §bAlumentum§r, place iron, sand (or Limestone Flux), and sulfur in the High Oven, then wait for the temperature to rise enough for the steel to craft.

§cMake sure it is hot enough before trying to craft alloys!

§rIf you use iron ore instead of iron ingots, you will get two steel per or§b§re.

§bPicking up an ingot will complete the quest.

§6Blood Magic Alchemy is a great source of Sulfur.
You will need 3,172 Coils to get to the correct size.

The Blast Furnace is simpler, so it might be worth investing in, but the High Oven is much more efficient.


Build a 3x3x3 cube, with the Hopper goes on top, then hammer the front. Pre-Heaters are placed on each side as an optional upgrade, and are powered from the top.

Place this block under a Mana Pool to unlock more crafting recipes!

§bRaven Feathers make great Fletching!
Right click with a wrench to toggle auto output, press M while holding to toggle bucket mode.

This is used to visualize some multiblock structures in JEI. 

Shouldn't have to say this, but don't actually do one of these crafts!

§6Most Multiblocks have a §9Capsule blueprint §6that is craftable and is used to place the entire Multiblock in just one click! Crafting one doesnt consume the MB parts, just the Paper, Buttons, and Lapis.§r
You can place either rings or more valves on top to increase the amount of fluid it can hold by 40 buckets each.

Unlock Alchemy all the way to Advanced Essentia Transport.

Also unlocks Hedge Alchemy.

§bUnneeded if skipping research, or if you plan on doing all of it by hand.

Right click to enter THE BENEATH.

Once you enter, look for the giant cavern.

§bThis is great place to run Pumpjacks and the Excavator!
Where these two liquids touch, sand is created, with a §bvery§r small chance of Aquamarine. (About 1:5000)
This is enough to build the smallest size tank, a 3x3x3 cube. The frame must be made out of Dynamic Tanks, and Glass or Valves can go on the faces.

Drop the correct petals, then some seeds into a filled Petal Apothecary.

Placing the correct blocks around the Pure Daisy will slowly transform them.

§bCheck out what other blocks can be transformed!
§r

The §aMunchdew§r will eat leaves in an area around itself as long as possible, then take a break when it runs out or fills up. Each leaf eaten will generate some amount of §3§1§9Mana§r.

§6Try Bonsai Pots for a source of leaves!

This hammer is mainly used to complete the multiblock structures from Immersive Engineering.

§bPlacing the tank into the Coke Oven will fill it with oil.
Place this anywhere on the structure.

§b§rLeft click or shift left click to change modes, then right click to place whatever item you want processed. The Profiling Bench does not need power.

§aItems can be piped in and out quite simply, so don't hesitate to set up a small automation for it!§r

Rockhounding can be an intimadating mod! One key thing to note is the §cred arrows§r in the Guide Book when building a machine. They indicate which way you should be facing when that part is placed. 

It is highly recommended to do the §dMineral Sizer§r quest below this one, to familiarize yourself with some of the concepts.

The Rockhounding questbook chapter will explain in depth how to get the most out of it, and if you need further help, feel free to stop by our §9Discord§r!

Simple ore doubling, as well as the start of 8x ore processing!

Assemble these as shown in the guide book you got in the previous quest, under §6Structures and Machines > Tier 2 Machines > Mineral Sizer.§r

Each Machine you assemble will need a §4Power Station§r, with Fuel and/or RF. Looking at which icons are blue on the top of the power station GUI will tell you which is needed. Fuel can be either §6Lava§r, §7Syngas§r, or any burnable item. §c(This one needs fuel)§r


Place 8 of any type §bCrushing Gears§r in the tanks, then crush your ore at the correct level in the Sizer Controller. You will need to remove the result from the Gangue Collecter before you can start the next batch. 

The §f§eServer§r is optional in any multiblock that includes one, so we can ignore it for now.


§cOne thing to note is that some of these machines do not perform well on a server, so it is recommended to use Compact Machines for your processing chain.
betterquesting:10.name:8: Intro to Rockhounding Multiblocks: The Mineral Sizer (2x Ore)

betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Crush Coal or Charcoal blocks in the Mineral Sizer at level 2 to get Cracked Coal.

Pipe the Cracked Coal and water into the Slurry Pond. Having more then one of these would be a good idea.

Pipe the Coal Slurry into the Cistern, and fill the top of the Burner with Water.

You will need a lot of§6 Fuel§r to bring the heat up initially.

A Gas Holder can be used in place of the Vessel in any of these multiblocks, and can hold 1,000 times the amount.

§bMaking two extra of these machines might come in handy later.

You can use the same tank for input as the output for Raw Syngas. If you choose not to, you will need an additional gas tank.

Pipe the Syngas into any Power Station that requires fuel.

Activate the Gas Pump by shift right clicking it with an empty hand.

§bMaking an extra one of these Machines might come in handy.
§1test§2test§3test§4test§5test§6test§7test§8test§a§9test§9§atest§btest§ctest§dtest§etest§ftest§ktest§l§8§l§rtest§a§ktest
Your first Obsidian.

Place this one block above the Obsidian, place the block of choice between the two, then supply with redstone.

This is mostly used for crushing stone smaller and smaller.

Place the pump over a water source block and supply redstone to the back. It has a chance to consume the source block over time.

Pipe water into the Evaporation Tank, wait, then pipe raw salt to the seasoning rack.


For the next quest, we'll be using the Brine from an intermediate step of evaporation, but the salt will be used later.


This is a slow process, and weather and biome will have an effect on how long it takes. It is advised to have multiple tanks evaporating at once.
Drop petals in here, along with some seeds, to craft your first magical flower, the Pure Daisy.
Right click with a petal on the grass, use regular bonemeal on it, then shear it down.
Aim your Mana Spreader at the pool and watch it fill up! Very slowly.

Place Greatwood around the Pure Daisy, and watch the sparkles.

Place Mossy Cobble around the Pure Daisy, and watch the sparkles.

§bDrop Grass and Cobble in water for Mossy.
Mana Spreaders are mainly used to transport the mana from collecting fVis/Fluxlowers to the Mana Pool.

Place diagonally to a 3x3 pool of water for best effect.

No need to automate, very low mana generation.

§cWill decay over one Hour!

Feed this one any fuel source.

§bHint: Look into an auto dropper above a pressure plate for automating.

§cWill decay over one Hour!

Place lava diagonally to this flower, but dont let it touch!

Tricky to automate, high mana generation. Requires a cool down after consuming a lava source, during which any lava consumed will not produce mana.

Shift-right click with the §2Wand of the Forest§r between generating flowers and the Mana Spreader, and the Mana Spreader and the Mana Pool.
If you place the Mana Spreader first, the flowers will be linked already.

Shift-right click the Mana Pool with the §2Wand of the Forest§r to change modes.

§6Use the Crucible to craft Alchemical Brass.

Place your Wand in the Arcane Workbench to add spells and recharge with Magic Crystals.

Explore dungeons and talk to Wizards to get better gear.
This is where you modify your Wands and add spells.

Throw this on various things to activate their true magical potential!

§U§cYou will need to use the Thaumonomicon to guide your way through this mod! §f

Use the quest chapter to get familiar with some of the concepts.

Use this on everything you can to learn more about the magical world around you.

It also comes with a handy Vis/Flux meter on the top left.

§bShift right clicking on chests might be a good way to rack up some knowledge.

Collect a bunch of those glowing crystals you've found growing around underground! 

They will spread over time if you aren't crafting too many arcane things in the area.

Your first arcane crafts will be here.

After learning how to make an Arcane Workbench in your Thaumonomicon, simply throw some more §dSalis Mundus§r on a plain old crafting table.
Place your wand in the center of the table, then place a spell in one of the five slots around it. Press the check mark to save your changes.

The Mixer requires both §aMechanical Power§r§r (connect an Axle right to the input), as well as an §6Ember§r supply (attach a Receptor to the input).

Can attach a Faucet right to the output!

This Machine will take quite a bit of microcrafting to assemble, but most of the items are made on the Profiling Bench and are quite cheap. §bCraft extra!§r

Assemble these as shown in the guide book you got in the previous quest, under §6Structures and Machines > Tier 1 Machines > Lab Blender.§r

Each Machine you assemble will need a §4Power Station§r, with Fuel and/or RF. Looking at which icons are blue on the top of the power station GUI will tell you which is needed. Fuel can be either §6Lava§r, §7Syngas§r, or any burnable item. §c(This one needs RF)§r

Life Crystals are primarily used to power the Animator, but can also be used to automate the Mortar and Infuser.

They can be recharged with Wight's Hearts.
Use this deep underground, and follow the sound to find an underwater Life Crystal Stalactite or muddy Middle Gem.
The second highest tier of Assembling Machine.
A basic magic building block.
Until you unlock the Ender IO Alloy Smelter, you'll need to do the in-world crafting method.
800 RF/t

Use the Sky Compass to find fallen Meteorites. Hidden deep inside will be a chest, with a press in it.
You will need to collect all four.

Place the item shown in JEI inside the Inscriber, along with the approprate press. 

Inscribers can be run with RF or AE power.
These are used in a great many things in this mod.
The Hydrogen Chloride can be made into Hydrochloric Acid, or you can follow Rockhounding's method.

Welcome to the start of Applied Energistics! You can build a storage system without the Controller and no Interfaces untill you unlock §bPlatinum§r.

Place some Certus Quartz inside a powered Charger, and wait till it sparkles. Also found rarely underground.

This can only be powered from the top and bottom, but items can be piped in and out from any side.
Crush up some Quartz or Fluix, mix it with sand, then drop in water for about 24 hours.
Throw the Nether Quartz, Redstone, and Charged Certus Quartz into a pool of water.
Place these around a water block, connect them to your network to give them power, then throw your seeds in.
Place your seeds inside here for the best growing speed. You can also create Fluix with this machine.
These go into your Drives, and are where your items are stored.
AE will only accept its own power, and one way to do that is by converting it through this.

Build a hollow cube, at least 3x3x3. The Controller goes bottom center, the middle layer can be glass, and the drain can go anywhere.

Pipe or bucket fluids in or out of the drain.

This is great for storing all your fluids.
The ME Drive holds 10 Drives.
These can be crafted into storage discs, or used in crafting CPU's.

Place your Crafting Storage connected to your network, then the Molecular Assembler next to a Interface, also connected to your network. 

Next place your incoded pattern into the Interface. 

If you go back to your terminal, you should be able to request your item to be crafted.
The Crafting Terminal is used to access all of your stored items, and can be used as a crafting grid. Hook it up with a cable to your network.
Craft items from your storage with the built in 3x3 crafting table.
Access your stored fluid from here.
You can also use the Energy Acceptor to make a coal generator instead.

The Pattern Terminal is where you create encoded Patterns, and the Interface Terminal allows you to access all of your ME Interfaces at once.

Place your Blank Pattern inside your Pattern Termnial, then open a recipe in jei. Press the plus icon to copy it to the terminal, then press the arrow to encode the pattern.
A much improved version of the Inscriber.
This very happy potato will be more then happy to be your companion!

How the Network interacts with other blocks.

The Interface has countless uses, but it is primarly used in autocrafting.
The ME Controller can handle up to 32 channels per face, as well as function as an Energy Acceptor.
This is one of the biggest quality of life upgrades since the ME Controller!

These are the basic cables that can connect your network.

You can use Cable Anchors to separate adjacent cables.
Place any combination of either of these blocks, plus at least one Crafting Storage, in a rectangular shape to create a Crafting Processing Unit.

Smart Cables have the same functionality as the fluix ones, but have the added use of displaying the amount of channels, or network blocks, connected to your network.

Dense Cables can carry 32 channels, instead of the 8 that the other two types can handle.
Place these inside the wireless access point.

Place this in the bottom slot of your security terminal, program it for access, then have them shift right click with it to lock it to them. 

Next just put it in the storage area of the Security Terminal.

These have a bit of a learning curve, but stick with it and your network capacity will explode.

P2P Tunnels come in pairs, normally. The output end will be toward your machines, and the input end is towards your controller. 

Once you place a pair of P2P's, shift right click with the Memory Card on the input, then right click on your output end to link them.

Channels go in and out the wide ends, and the smaller ends just need to be connected to your network like any other network block.



Shift right click to clear your Memory Card.
Place the Storage Bus against any storage to have the network recognize it.
Some useful items to have.

Throw the §dSalis Mundus§r on the Caldron to turn it into a Crucible. Fill with water, then heat.

This can be a messy process, with wasted Essentia converting into §5Flux§r and polluting the atmosphere. This can cause §5Void Rifts§r, which can destroy blocks if left unattended. Look in the top left corner of the screen while holding the §6Thaumometer§r to check your Vis/Flux levels. The Dark Purple is how much §5Flux§r is in the chunk.

Use §bQuartz Slivers§r to clean up after a craft, but make sure to unlock the research first!

§6This will be used to make Brass until you get access to Zinc.

Right click on the top of the Crucible or drop items in.

This can be used as a light source, or to heat your Crucible.

§cThe Thaumometer can not see what is inside, you need the goggles for that. Don't drop it in!

Sand, coal, and Mana Powder are all you'll need to craft this.

Alumentum burns four times longer then regular coal, and can be thrown to cause a small explosion.

§bCan also be used as High Oven and Blast Furnace fuel to great effect.
Right click on the tank with the Mod Wrench until it shows purging Brine. Then all you need to do is pipe the Brine into a tank for storage.
Heating up already hot metal to create an infernally hot ingot.

With Nature's Compass you can choose a biome, and it will point to the closest one.

§6Amber is found inside Hollow Hills.
Osmium is found in the Beneath

§d§5Raw Voidstone§r is found in the Beneath.

Items can be piped in and out for basic automation.

Shift-right click on your altar with the§d Diviner§r to show a holographic layout in order to upgrade to the next tier.

Using the §bSacrificial Dagger§r next to the altar will damage you to fill your altar by a small amount, while hitting mobs next to an altar with the §bDagger of Sacrifice§r will insta-kill them for some blood.
Once you have some oil, you can make the Small Storage Crate, or if you have already gotten some void crystals you can create the medium variety.

Place §6§r8§r of any type of rune in a ring one level below your blood altar to upgrade it to level 2.

§cOnly the four side runes can be upgraded on a tier 2 Altar! §rOnce upgraded to the tier 3 and higher, all eight take effect.

§rThese are the basic runes, they can be upgraded to modify your Blood Altar in diferent ways.

You'll need a lot of §eSlate Dust§r coming up soon, so set up automation for it as soon as you can.

Now that you have some blank runes, you can go ahead and craft the Runic Matrix!

§bClaiming this quest will unlock the research for Infusion.

I've pre filtered the two needed fluids in the rewarded Ampoules, but you may need this later on. Most machines will auto filter, except the one in the next quest.


Inside the Fluidpedia, use the Ampoule on whichever fluid you want to be filtered, then you can use it to set the filters in RH Tanks or Gas Holders/Vessels.

§cIn the current version of Rockhounding, the letter sorting is broken! Use the arrows instead.

Assemble this as shown in the guide book, then set the filters in the fluid input as shown in JEI to create Sodium Hydroxide. §6Be sure to always match Primary and Secondary sides!§r

Pipe the Saturated Brine and Water into the fluid input. Start the process in the Electrochemical CSTR.

If you've done everything correctly, Sodium Hydroxide should start outputting on the bottom.

§cThe Power Station needs RF and Fuel.
Magical Dust?

Items go in the top, and the controls are on the bottom.

Each of the items will need to be blended for the next step.

§cThe Power Station needs RF.§r

Rock Crushing machines might be your best bet here.

Assemble the Lab Oven as shown in the guide book. It is highly recommended to set up a separate Lab Oven to process each of the upcoming products.


§bOptional: To set up automation with a Server, place the Server File in the center slot and scroll to the desired recipe with the arrows. Next chose if you want it repetable or not and how many times it should run. Then place it in the top row and active the server. The Lab Oven will then run the recipes defined by the Server Files in order once you activate it.

Assemble another Gas Purifier with an Air Compresser pumping air into the input.

You won't need the Particulate Collector for purifying air.

§f§nWhat is QMD?

§9Quantum Minecraft Dynamics §fis a mod that brings §5High-Energy Particle Physics§f to Minecraft. While it may seem complicated at first glance, the mod becomes much more understandable when you understand the concepts behind it. 

Besides this in-game quest book guide, QMD § also has its own §2Guide Book§r already present in the Akashic Tome (albeit incomplete). A more complete version can be found on the §Q§Q§2QMD Github Wiki.§f

Of course, the §N§2Nuclearcraft Official Discord§r also has channels to discuss high-energy particle smashing! Make sure to check out §7#qmd§r for support.

Without further ado, let's get into the tutorial!


§nQuick Summary§r

In short, QMD revolves around §6producing, manipulating and utilising §5particles§r, via §3specially designed Multiblocks§r, for various recipes. These recipes produce §enew items§r or even §5new types of particles§r, which can then be used in further recipes. In addition, QMD contains other fun things, such as §cpowerful weapons§r or §6extreme power generation§r!


§nBrief Introduction to Multiblocks§r

As mentioned before, particles are manipulated in various ways in QMD's various multiblocks. There are three types of multiblocks in QMD:

§3-Accelerators
§a-Particle Chambers
§7-Vacuum Chambers§r

Particles are produced and accelerated in §3Accelerators§r, then used for recipes in §aParticle Chambers§r and §7Vacuum Chambers§r. All Multiblocks will be covered in subsequent quests, and more details can also be found on the §2QMD Github Wiki§r.

Since the entire mod revolves around particles, it is only natural that we understand them before we do anything involving them.


§nWhat are Particles?§r

Unlike most mods that handle items, fluids or even gases, QMD instead deals with particles. Each particle has a set of properties that can be viewed in §2JEI§r. 

Much like how regular §eitems§f are stored in §astacks§r, QMD §5particles§f are stored in §"§2"particle stacks"§f. However, unlike item stacks, particle stacks cannot be held by the player. Instead, §pparticle stacks§f can only be manipulated in §9QMD's§f §3specialised Multiblock Machines§f, and transported via §7Beamline Pipes§r.

The §aTarget Chamber§r is a §aParticle Chamber§r, and it allows you to smash your high-velocity particles into items to obtain §enew items§f, and even, in some cases, §5new particles§f! It's the primary multiblock in which recipes are processed, although more will be unlocked later on.


§nConstruction§r

A visualisation of a Target Chamber can be found in §2JEI§r (5x5x5) and on the §2QMD§f §2Github Wiki§f.

§r§nTarget Chamber Recipes§r

In order to process a recipe, the Target chamber must be supplied with:
- §6Power§r

§fThe §4amount of particles§r required for a recipe to be processed once is the amount shown in §2JEI§r. The resulting §5particle§f§5s§e §fand their particle stack properties can be seen in the §2Target Chamber GUI§r. More details on how the resulting particle stack properties are calculated can be found in the "Target Chamber Maths" quest.

You've finally done it: the laws of physics §c§rbend§r* before your engineering might, as you hit rocks together so hard they make §6§rgold§r. Now, you need to put those skills to the test: §d§eP-Type Doped Silicon §fis your aim.

§nSafety Precautions§r

Before switching on your Linear Accelerator§f, first:

2. Make sure that the Linear Accelerator§f's §9total cooling§f exceeds the §ctotal heating§f.

4. Make sure that the supercooler cooling loop has been set up, and is fast enough to supply the Accelerator with the required coolant.


§nSwitching it all on§r

Now, simply place §eDiborane Canisters§f in the Ion Source§f and give the Linear Accelerator Controller§f a §4redstone signal§f, and the Target Chamber§f should start producing §eP-Type Doped Silicon§f.

§nConstruction§r

§nRecipes§r

In order for a recipe to work, both input particle beams must have a §bfocus§f above 5 and §6energy§f above that shown in §2JEI§f. §nRecipes§r

In order to create §6exotic matter§f, the required particle beams as stated in §2JEI§f must have an §6energy§f of §60eV§f (with the exception of §5glueballs§f, which can have any energy) and sufficient §bfocus§f for the recipe. The number of ticks it takes to create 1mb of exotic matter is the amount of particles required for the recipe, divided by the amount of particles in the particle stack. If there are two beams, the time taken will be the larger of the two beams.

§eBSCCO §fis an advanced §6high-temperature superconductor alloy§f. It's used in wire form to create numerous incredibly advanced machines; its most notable use, of course, is in §eElite Processors§r.

§eStrontium§f is an important material §conly obtainable via QMD§f. It's required to manufacture §eBSCCO§f, a superconductor material required for further progression in the mod.

The first way is obtaining Strontium§f from §eLight Fission Waste§f. While this method is feasible for obtaining trace amounts of Strontium§f, it is slow and takes a long time to obtain mass amounts of Strontium§f.

Now that you know how §5particles§r work, it's time to make use of those concepts to construct your first §3QMD Multiblock§r! This quest will talk about §3Linear Accelerators§f (also known as §3LINACs§f), the first Accelerator you will build.


§nLinear Accelerators

§3LINACs§f are your gateway to §9§1§9QMD§f, providing your first method of §5particle manipulation§r. Being an entry-level Accelerator§f, they also produce the particles required for any recipe in QMD§f. 


§nConstruction§r

A visualisation of an empty and filled §3Linear Accelerator§r is avaliable in §2JEI§r and the §2QMD Github Wiki§r.

Casing Material: §7Accelerator Casing/Glass§r

Dimensions: 5 blocks wide, 5 blocks tall, variable length (Min. 6 blocks, Max. 100 blocks), with a continuous line of §7Accelerator Beam Blocks§f in the centre

Required blocks on long sides:
- §7Linear Accelerator Controller
§r- §72 Accelerator Coolant Vents§f in §aInput§e§f and §cOutput§f mode
§-- §7Accelerator Energy Port§f

Required blocks at the ends of the Accelerator, in the centre:
- §7Accelerator Ion source§f facing inwards at one end 
- §7Accelerator Beam Port§f in §cOutput§r mode at the other end 

The particle stack is produced by the §7Ion Source§r and exits the Accelerator via the §7Beam Port§r. 

§cNote:§r The Linear Accelerator can also be used to accelerate existing particle stacks by replacing the Accelerator Ion Source with an Accelerator Beam Port on input mode, then piping the particle stack in via that beam port.


The remaining empty space in the Linear Accelerator can now be filled up with §7Accelerator Components§r (§bQuadrapole Magnets§r and §dRF Cavities§r, covered in relevant quests below), to accelerate particles, and §9Coolers§r (covered in "Passive Cooling"), to cool the Accelerator.


§nRequirements§r

All Accelerators have similar requirements for operation.

1. Accelerators must be supplied with §6power§r to operate. 

2. Accelerators must be cooled with §9coolers§r (passive cooling) and §1coolant§r (active cooling) in order to not §coverheat§r and §cexplode§r. Cooling mechanics are covered in the quests above.

3. Accelerators are switched on via a §credstone signal§r. The output particle's energy is §c(redstone strength)§r/15 of the §6maximum particle energy§f, which is covered in the "RF Cavity" quest.

In addition, for a LINAC to produce §5particles§r, the §7Ion Source§r must be supplied with §efilled canisters§r. Ion sources are covered in "Ion Source".

§lPassive Cooling Requirement:§r The §9sum of the cooling§f from all §9Accelerator Coolers §e§fmust §6exceed§r the §cmaximum heating§f (the sum of all component heating and external heating) of the accelerator§f. 

Both the cooling and max§c§fimum heating§f can be seen by hovering over the §cheat bar§r (second bar from the left) in the §2Accelerator GUI§r. 


§nFull Explanation§r

Each component (e.g Quadrapole, RF Cavity) placed in an Accelerator §cheats it up§r by the amount shown in the component block's §6tooltip§r (Note: This is the heating value of §6the entire component§r, not just one block!). Thus, §9Accelerator Coolers§r are required to cool the Accelerator.

§9Accelerator Coolers§f can be placed in §6any remaining unoccupied space§r in an Accelerator, and they cool the Accelerator by the amount shown in their §6tooltip§r. However, much like §2Nuclearcraft: Overhaul §fcoolers§f, they have placement rules regarding where they can be placed (next to an electromagnet, next to an RF Cavity, etc.).

Much like how §aitem stacks§r have properties (amount of items in a stack), §2particle stacks§r also have their own properties. However, unlike item stacks, particle stacks have 3 properties:

§4- Amount (pu/t)
§6- Energy (eV)
§b- Focus§f

§4Amount§r is the amount of particles, measured in particle units (pu). Particles are produced at a given rate, measured in particle units per tick (pu/t), and that amount §ccannot§r be modified by Accelerators.

§6Energy§r is the energy of the particles, measured in Electron Volts (eV). It can be increased or decreased by Accelerators.

§bFocus§r is how focused or confined the particles are. It can be increased by Accelerators.


§nIntroduction to QMD Recipes§r

All recipes involving particles require particle stacks to have a §bminimum focus§f, and §6energy§r within a certain §6energy range (e.g 10-20 MeV)§f for the recipe to work (relevant values can be seen in §2JEI§f). Recipes require a §4cumulative amount of particles§r to be completed, thus allowing the speed of a recipe to be calculated with (pu required)/(pu/t).

§A§fAs most newly-created particles start out with no §6energy §fand barely any §bfocus§f, §3Accelerators§e §fare used in order to get particle stacks to the relevant § §6energy§f and §bfocus§f§f. How §3Accelerators§f do this, and how they are constructed will be covered in "QMD 102: The Linear Accelerator" and relevant quests.

Particle stacks cannot be handled directly by the player. Instead, they can only be transported via §7beam blocks§r (inside multiblocks) and §7beamline pipes§r (outside multiblocks). They can be imagined as §6beams§r travelling through beam blocks to their destination. 

As beamline pipes cannot be turned on their own, §3Beam Diverters§r are required to rotate the direction of a beam, and will be covered in a later quest.


Particle stacks also §close focus§r for every block they travel! The amount lost per block is based on the §battenuation rate (default 0.02)§r and the §4pu/t§r of the particle stack, via the equation:

§bFocus Lost per Block§r = §b
attenuation rate§r * (1 + |§dcharge§r|*(§4pu/t§r / 10000)^0.5)

The charge of a particle can be found in §2JEI§r, under particle properties.

If the focus is less than or equal to 0, the particle stack will not travel any further. Thus, make sure to minimise the distance particles travel in your QMD setups to minimise focus loss!

§lActive Cooling Requirement:§r An accelerator§f must be §nconstantly supplied§r with an §1active coolant§r, whose §ctemperature§r is §6below§r the §cmaximum temperature§r (the lowest maximum operating temperature out of all components) of the accelerator.

The accelerator's current temperature and maximum temperature can be viewed in the §2Accelerator GUI§r. 


§nFull Explanation§r

Components are only capable of operating when they are §9cooled§r below their §cmaximum operating temperature§r, as seen in the §6tooltip§r of the block used to construct that component. Thus, §1active coolant§r is required to lower the accelerator's temperature.

Active coolants §fcool an accelerator§f to their own temperature, provided that the §9passive cooling§r requirement is met (see the quest "Passive Cooling"). Valid active coolants§f and their temperatures can be seen in §2JEI§f via Accelerator Controllers.


When an accelerator is supplied with active coolant via the §9input§r coolant vent, it is converted into the resultant hot coolant (as seen in the JEI recipe), which is output from the §coutput§r cooler vent. Coolant§f use rate as well as exhaust coolant output rate can be seen via the §9coolant bar§f (third bar from the left) in the §2Accelerator GUI§r.

§cNote:§r Used up coolant must constantly be emptied from the accelerator for it to work, otherwise new coolant cannot be input into the accelerator to cool it and the accelerator will §coverheat and explode§r!


§r§nSupercooler Loop§r

§fWith the exception of water, §nall active coolants§f are output in their gaseous forms in the same ratio as their gas:liquid conversion ratio in a supercooler. Thus, you can form a §6closed loop of active coolant§f by pumping §cexhaust coolant§f from the output coolant vent  into a Supercooler, then pumping the §9cooled active coolant§f back into the input coolant vent, with no loss in active coolant§f.

Beam Multiplication is the concept of increasing the §4amount§r of particles in a beam by using recipes that have output beams with a larger amount than the input beam. This can be used to §espeed up recipes§r in the Target Chamber, produce rare particle beams with §4large amounts of particles§r, or even §6produce more power§r in the Nucleosynthesis Chamber!

So, how do we actually multiply a beam? We just need to follow this fundamental principle:

§oAny Particle Chamber recipe with an output beam whose amount is greater than 1pu can emit a beam with more particles than the original beam.§r


§nExample: Multiplying a Proton Beam§r

Let's try to multiply a proton beam. We are looking for §aTarget Chamber recipes§r that produce output beams with more than 1pu. One good example is the §eproton-silicon recipe§r, which outputs a 3pu proton beam. While the recipe only has a cross-section of 20%, we can get a full proton beam by increasing the §etarget chamber efficiency§r with detectors until we get an output proton beam with 3 times the amount of the original beam. This means that if the input beam was a §410kpu/t§r proton beam, the output beam can reach a maximum of §430kpu/t§r!

We can multiply the beam further by sending the §430kpu/t§r proton beam into a §asecond target chamber with silicon§r to get a §490kpu/t beam§r, and repeat until we get a beam with a satisfactory amount.


§nBeware of Focus Loss§r

However, there are practical limits to how much you can multiply particle beams. The more particles you have in a beam, the larger the §bfocus loss per block§r (calculated in the quest "Transporting Particles"). Therefore, avoid multiplying beams too much or transporting large beams over too large of a distance!

This quest covers various calculations for Nucleosynthesis Recipes, such as §erecipe time§r and §crate of heat production§r.

The §4amount of particles§r required for a recipe to be processed once is the amount shown in §2JEI§r. Thus, the time taken for a recipe to process, in ticks, is given as the amount of particles required for the recipe (e.g §4155.9kpu§r) divided by the amount of particles in the particle stack (e.g §410000 pu/t§r). In this case, the recipe will take ~16t to process.

When a recipe is complete, it produces both output fluids and §cheat§r. The rate of heat production is given by the amount of heat produced (e.g. §c17.6kH§r) divided by the recipe time given above (e.g. 15.59t). In this case, the rate of heat production will be §c~1130H/t§r. This heat is converted into §8Hot Mercury§r, as covered in the quest "Cooling Fusion".

Much like §3Accelerators§r, the Nucleosynthesis Chamber must also be §9cooled passively§r. However, unlike Accelerators, the Nucleosynthesis Chamber produces a useful cooling product: §8Hot Mercury§r, which can be used to generate §6large amounts of power§r in an §2NC:O Turbine§r!


§nCooling§r

In order to get rid of the heat produced, §7Vacuum Heaters§r must be placed inside the Nucleosynthesis Chamber to §9cool§r it. Much like Accelerator Coolers, Vacuum Heaters also have placement rules regarding where they can be placed. Both the total cooling and heating§f can be seen by hovering over the §cheat bar§r (second bar from the right) in the §2Chamber GUI§r. The §9total cooling§r must exceed the §ctotal heating§r, otherwise the chamber will §cexplode§r!


§nPower§r

Cooling the Nucleosynthesis Chamber also produces Hot Mercury. The §8rate of hot mercury production (mb/t)§r is equal to the §crate of heat production (H/t)§r (calculated in the quest "Nucleosynthesis Recipes") multiplied by the §eoutput efficiency§r, which is given by the §crate of heat production§r divided by the §9total cooling§r. Thus, you should ensure that the total cooling is as close to the rate of heat production as possible!

As the rate of heat production is variable and dependent on both the recipe you choose and the §4amount of particles§r in the input beam, it is recommended that you calculate the rate of heat production beforehand, then place Vacuum Heaters to get total cooling as close as possible to the rate of heat production.
